<subSubSection id="C33D65512956FFF4FC6AE2F6FB8048E7" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B9836DA2956FFF4FC6AE2F6FB8048E7" blockId="22.[836,1528,1253,1466]" pageId="22" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis id="B953EAC82956FFF4FC6AE2F6FB01485F" box="[956,1228,1254,1282]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="21">Diagnostic Features.</emphasis>
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D592956FFF4FCBEE31AFB24487A" authority="Deeleman-Reinhold" authorityName="Deeleman-Reinhold" box="[872,1257,1290,1319]" class="Arachnida" family="Ochyroceratidae" genus="Speocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pongo">
<emphasis id="B953EAC82956FFF4FCBEE31AFC11487A" box="[872,988,1290,1319]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="21">S. pongo</emphasis>
Deeleman-Reinhold
</taxonomicName>
but differs from the latter in the (
<number id="3DEF24FD2956FFF4FBFDE33FFBF54811" box="[1067,1080,1327,1356]" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" value="1.0">1</number>
) pigmentation design in the cephalothorax, (
<number id="3DEF24FD2956FFF4FBC2E344FBE8482C" box="[1044,1061,1364,1393]" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" value="2.0">2</number>
) color of sternum, (
<number id="3DEF24FD2956FFF4FAFBE344FAF0482C" box="[1325,1341,1364,1393]" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" value="3.0">3</number>
) tibia IV with only two spines, (
<number id="3DEF24FD2956FFF4FBF1E369FBF448CB" box="[1063,1081,1401,1430]" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" value="4.0">4</number>
) femur II as long as femur IV, and (
<number id="3DEF24FD2956FFF4FC98E38DFC9348E7" box="[846,862,1437,1466]" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" value="5.0">5</number>
) longer pedipalps.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33D65512956FFF4FC72E3F7FABC4B10" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B9836DA2956FFF4FC72E3F7FABC4B10" blockId="22.[836,1529,1511,1613]" pageId="22" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis id="B953EAC82956FFF4FC72E3F7FBF84B59" box="[932,1077,1511,1540]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="21">Etymology.</emphasis>
Patronym, in honor of Dr. Robert R. Jackson for his untiring interest and pioneering works on the behaviour of jumping spiders.
</paragraph>
